My guess would be that it triggers a compiler error because of the missing braces {}. However, reading <a href="http://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/switch" rel="nofollow">http://en.cppreference.com/w/c/language/switch</a> and <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/66k51h7a.aspx" rel="nofollow">https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/66k51h7a.aspx</a>, I am starting to wonder about that. Both pages claim that <i>switch(expression)</i> can be followed by any statement, not just compound ones.<p>That seems to make it legal C. It also would make<p><pre><code>  switch(i) x += 1;
</code></pre>
and possibly even<p><pre><code>  switch(i) foo: x += 1;
</code></pre>
valid (but nonsensical) C. Chances are that the standard contains special wording that prohibits the latter two, though. If not, this is useful to know for the obfuscated C contest (more so if you can jump to that label)
